<DOC><DOCNO> AP890106-0114 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-06-89 1322EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-LunchtimeRobberies 1stLd-Writethru a0549 01-06 0217</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Lunchtime Robberies, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0549,0216</SECOND><HEAD>Inmate Charged With Robbing Banks on His Lunch Hour</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS next-to-last graf to CORRECT crime to manslaughter stedrobbery.</HEAD><DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An inmate on a work-release program hasbeen charged with robbing banks on his lunch hour.   Lawrence Terry Jordan, 39, who worked as a laborer at a statemaintenance complex, was charged Wednesday in two hold-ups Nov. 28and Dec. 9 in which a man who said he had a bomb stole a total of$3,230, authorities said.   Jordan was charged after he began offering cash gifts to friendsand a corrections officer saw a broadcast about the holdups andrecognized him, authorities said.   Inmates at the maintenance complex are dropped at their worksites in the morning and picked up in the evening. There are norestrictions on where they can go to eat, said CorrectionsDepartment spokesman Francis X. Archibald.   Jordan, who is serving a 15-year sentence for manslaughter, wastransferred after his arrest from a dormitory-type work center to aprison cell, Archibald said.   Jordan began his sentence in 1981 and entered the work-releaseprogram in 1984, said Archibald. The spokesman defended the 23-yearprogram, saying it has had few problems and allows inmates to help``pay their room and board.''</TEXT></DOC>